defaultIn Kirklees, the last decade has seen a number of changes in the way the authority addresses climate change issues and communicates with the public. Initially, resources were focussed on 
defaultraising awareness ofdefault 
defaultclimate changedefault 
defaultthrough the Council’s ‘Green Ambi
defaulttion’ environmental 
defaultprogramme, 
defaultand explaining the scientific argument to engage people in the broader consequence of rising temperatures and what they could do at an individual level. This was in line with national media and communicating the findings from
default key research such as the Stern Report. 
default&#xa0;
default4.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs time progressed, and council priorities 
defaultevolved
default, messages which were originally about ‘tackling climate change’ became focussed on 
defaultreducing carbon emissionsdefault. Generally speaking, the message that climate change i
defaults real and happening
default is to an extent 
defaultunderstood and accepted, and the focus moved to reducing the key cause of climate change – carbon emissions. This mirrored local authority data collection requirements such as those set out in Local Area Agreements and 
defaultNational Indicators (185 and 186). 
